editorial_summary.overview: Israeli street food snacks dished up in a trendy, laid-back counter-serve with sidewalk seats.

name: Miznon Singapore

reviews.text: Crowded for lunch so do come early. The pitas are warm and soft - easily the best I have ever had. The portions are big and filling. My favourite was the candy brisket pita and moussaka pita.

Nice plain pitas and friendly staff!

The plain pitas was soft and fluffy, the best I’ve had. It is my first time having Israeli cuisine and I find the hummus have a bitter aftertaste. The food was on the oilier side and definitely a bit pricey as well.

The two young female servers were friendly, chirpy and helpful.

My only gripe is the music is a little loud and if you’re sitting indoors, you’re gonna be shouting talking to your friends and stinking of the kitchen!

recently had a fantastic experience at this F&B establishment with a focus on Israel cuisine. The pita bread was exceptional, providing an authentic taste that truly impressed. A heartfelt thank you to the incredible service staff, especially Kervin and Maria, who made my dining experience truly memorable. Their attention to detail and warm hospitality added an extra layer of enjoyment to my visit. And let's not forget the delightful surprise of their awesome tatami tiramisu – the best I've had so far! Highly recommended for a top-notch dining experience. ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐

Best pita I had ever had, so fluffy. Got the lamb shrawma and beef brisket pitas and both were filled with generous amount of meat and condiments. They were so delicious and not greasy. Fried calamari was also the perfect side to have. The israeli tiramisu was a perfect way to end the meal, though it can be quite a big one.

My second visit (last time I tried the Candy Brisket Pita)! I'm doing Folded Cheeseburger Pita now (technically this was last week).

As always, the jive and vibe here is fantastic. The meat, vegetables and dressing is generous. This time, the sauce didn't drip out. 😎

Imma come back for more!

editorial_summary.overview: Contemporary hub on the waterfront, offering Italian cuisine, a rooftop bar & club nights.

name: Monti At 1-Pavilion Italian Restaurant

reviews.text:
Super nice and value for money Italian restaurant with spectacular view!

We ordered the 3 course $55 set lunch. The seafood stew in the photo has a $16 extra charge but I find it rich and tasty and worth the extra. The food is super fresh and delicately presented. Set meal does not include tea/coffee.

Service is excellent and professional

Ambience is peaceful and quiet. View excellent.

Will return

Amazing view of the waterfront and Marina Bay Sands. Menu was extensive and food excellent albeit slight issue with the quail dish.. however, easily rectified by the manager.

Service was a bit slow and staff seemed untrained. Big props to Carol the door hostess as she was lovely and accommodating considering we did not have a reservation :)

When you walk into a restaurant such as Monti, you deserve to raise your expectations to match. The food was just so mediocre, with flavours mismatched and nothing stood out. The Manila clam pasta was horrible and weird, the bean soup tasted too beaney, tomatoes salad tasted overripe, with no flavour to enjoy. Not worth returning...

Davide hosted my friend and I with excellent hospitality service. The view was amazing, food was perfect, the wine complemented it really well too! The staffs were very attentive and helped to refill our wine and water too. Definitely coming back for more!

Lovely view of the Marina Bay, service was attentive n friendly , engaging in appropriate small talk .

Generous portions, love the cod bites+ artichoke,  was SO GOOD.

Mr Monti cocktail and super strong Long Island tea were to die for !

formatted_address: 10 Bayfront Ave, B1 - 42 / 41 Galleria Level, Singapore 018956
name: Mott 32 Singapore

reviews.text:
Mott 32 at Marina Bay Sands pleasantly surprised me with its exquisite Chinese cuisine. 🥢 Despite expecting a steakhouse, the diverse menu offerings showcased the restaurant's culinary versatility. Each dish was a delightful fusion of flavors, leaving me thoroughly impressed with the quality and taste. 🍜 The elegant design of the restaurant added to the overall dining experience, with its chic ambiance and comfortable seating options providing the perfect backdrop for a memorable meal. 🏮

One aspect that stood out was the efficiency of the service. Despite the bustling atmosphere, the staff ensured that the food was served promptly, allowing for a seamless dining experience. ⏱️ Whether it's a quick lunch or a leisurely dinner, Mott 32 delivers on both speed and quality, making it a top choice for any occasion.

Overall, I highly recommend Mott 32 to anyone looking for exceptional Chinese cuisine in Marina Bay Sands. With its delicious food, stylish ambiance, ample seating, and efficient service, it's a dining destination worth visiting time and time again.

By far the best roast duck and roast pork I have ever tasted. Wow...their roast duck, first served with its crispy skin, and then the premium cut meat to go with the wrap style. Finally, the balance of the meat in minced style to go with baby lettuce. I would highly recommend their roast duck if you have a group of 4 people and above to share.

Roast pork - carefully selected cut and you can see how much love they put into roasting the pork.

Maybe I am bias as I love chinese food, I feel every dish is a perfect 10 here.

Dress code - strictly no open toe shoes and gym clothes.

Service is impeccable here. They served us an ice cream decorated plate as we mentioned it is meant for a birthday celebration during reservation.

Mott 32 seamlessly marries Chinese cuisine with western ingredients, resulting in dishes that are both innovative and modern. From the moment you step foot inside, the ambiance exudes sophistication and elegance, setting the stage for an unforgettable dining experience. The attention to detail is impeccable, from the stylish decor to the impeccable service provided by the attentive staff. The truffle chicken is definitely a must have. Unfortunately didnt manage to try the duck but have tried it in HK before. Food is excellent but I would say it can be better for its price.

A friend told me their Peking Duck  is really good so was so excited to try it but unfortunately it was sold out 😩

Besides the Peking Duck, we did had a good “pricey” lunch. 😄

The food was good, I especially like the Signature crispy sugar coated Peking duck bun and their Hot & Sour soup.

The service was good and efficient.

The venue is simply cosy with old charms vibes.

It’s pricey because of their premium proteins.

A restaurant that is well decorated, good ambience and very IG-friendly. Will be more catered for foreigners who love Chinese food that are cooked and presented in a posh manner. Overall, an over rated restaurant for Chinese food considering the hefty price one needs to pay. The taste and flavour of the dishes are reasonable but not exceptional.

adr_address: 38 Maxwell Rd, #01-01/02 Airview Building, Air View Building, Singapore 069116
formatted_address: 38 Maxwell Rd, #01-01/02 Airview Building, Air View Building, Singapore 069116
name: Mouth Restaurant - 地茂馆

reviews.text:
Dimsum was fantastic,
The longish spring roll was super tasty and unique.
The truffle veg dumpling was also a crowd favourite amongst colleagues.
I also forgot how many servings of the fried bean curd rolls we got, it was so good.
Custard bun was amazing too!

Everything was good actually, and not too expensive also, would come again!

No comments about service since we came on the eve of cny eve. Though it was nice that they still had tables when I reserved one week before

A nice cosy place for a birthday lunch. The food was served quite promptly after we placed the order, even though the place was full. Staff members were polite and efficient.

We ordered fish maw soup and the flavour was just right, not too salty. Prawn balls with cereal and they tasted fresh and nice. Peking duck was wrapped in egg skin and there were mixed reviews from a few of us, with some who felt the egg skin stole the attention from the duck skin. Steamed garoupa was a little tough but fresh and tasty still. Crispy spring chicken was surprisingly nice, even the breast meat did not taste dry and tough. Tim sum siew mai and har kao were good. We especially like the fried banana with prawn which was coated generously with sesame seeds on top and that added flavour and fragrance for us sesame lovers. Dessert Gui Ling Gao and mango pomelo sago were good to wrap up the meal 😋 we were so engrossed with eating and forgot to take photos of most of the earlier dishes 😅

Thanks for making the day for the group of us. We had an enjoyable birthday lunch!

Visited their Maxwell branch again, for the second time now, for annual Reunion gathering and food was of decent spread.

However, it might be due to the packed list of reservations and limited time set aside for each seating, CNY sets were served all at once and we didn’t get to enjoy the food fully when hot.

And there were limited sets for CNY. Do check before you book the place for CNY reunions or be disappointed with limited choices. The 5 of us had to make do with a CNY set for 4, and additional dim sum dishes, which we didn’t mind, but for individuals who would prefer to have a set for each diner, this is something to note.

That aside, we all found their dim sums better and I would recommend the spot for their dim sum if you are in the area and looking for some dim sum to fill your tummy with.

Celebrated dad’s birthday there and ordered their 7 course dinner plus additional seafood claypot toufu. All the dishes were delicious, and portion is generous. Very valued for money. Will visit again to try their dim sum which is only for lunch time. Only downside is restaurant is a bit old. But overall fantastic dinning experience.

Had our CNY dinner on Day 2 here with a family of 10 and enjoyed the food (except the glutinous rice which was rather mushy and flavourless). Service was noticeably not great, only the Filipino server was attentive and caring but the other staff seemed overwhelmed and grumpy!

vicinity: 38 Maxwell Road, #01-01/02 Airview Building, Air View Building

adr_address: 30 Victoria St, #02-01B C, Singapore 187996
name: New Ubin Seafood CHIJMES

reviews.text: Very good quality food with reasonable pricing. We were offered a vip room so 8 of us had privacy. Service staff is super friendly and very responsive even though the place was very busy. Special mention for the pepper crab, it's firm and flavorful. The Angus beef is another standout. Overall a very enjoyable dinner!

Pretty decent chills crab the restaurant is okay nice location in city area of Singapore. Tourist regional area pretty nice local food but only a bit too salty for the veggies and cabbage salt level are extremely high here but overall tastes good probably msg as well so it's good food to try local flavors and non fine dining experience mass market stuff

First time here with the fam, food was great. Great recommendations recommended by their staff Chris. Excellent servicing. Chris’s service would make me want to visit this restaurant next time im here in Singapore.

Chanced upon this nice restaurant, tucked in a corner on the 2nd floor of Chijmes. It serves really good food late night. The mee goreng and veg had wok hey flavour, tequila chicken was flavourful as well. Waiter was engaging and service was great. Would come back for another visit

Unfortunately, overrated.
-Getting their top seller food on menu - by right cant go wrong but it does this evening.
Wagyu platter isn’t as good as 1st outlet disappointed with standard dropped.

The amount of food no alcohol $300+ after card 10% discount. Is extremely expensive for average taste food and ambience.

adr_address: 110 Amoy St, #01-01, Singapore 069930
name: North Singapore (By Miznon)

reviews.text: Great service crew and amazing recommendations. Eggplants tasted quite burnt, the smokiness was overpowering. Figs were interesting. Crab pasta was not bad. We love the complimentary bread so much! Extensive drinks list! Best to reserve a table in advance.

Came here twice. The hummus with prawns is the best hummus ive had. So smooth, creamy and it goes really well with prawns to my surprise! The charred cauliflower is excellent, very fragrant and the serving is huge, literally a whole ball of cauliflower. Broccolli was good, but cauliflower even better. The mushroom papardelle pasta was better than the crab pasta. But both great as well! Love it. The focaccia bread is excellent. Staff is lovely, although the restaurant is quite noisy. I’ll definitely be back to try other dishes again.

Recommend to book in advance!

I have to admit that while I’m excited about trying new cuisine, Israeli cuisine to be precise in this case, there is still a slight bit of trepidation there. Since I’m not sure if the taste of the food suits my palates and there is no menu on the website to know the selection of food. My worries prove to be unfounded when I take a look at the seasonal menu when in the restaurant. In fact, there are so many choices that I want to order at least four of them. But with my limited stomach, I decide on getting 2 dishes instead. And I totally happy with my choices!

The food here is so delicious and flavorful. In fact, there is lots of similarities between Israeli and Greek cuisine. Think olive oil, lemon and tangy cream. The difference is Israeli cuisine has the middle eastern herbs added for the extra oomph and mild pungency. So if you are into Greek cuisine, you will definitely like it here.

The place is like this rustic Middle Eastern tavern with the cement walls, geometric wood panels, soft yellow lights, sand-coloured tapestry and florid tiles. It feels so cosy with a light air of mystique.

Service is very good, helpful and friendly. At lunch, the dining experience here is great. At dinner, the dining experience is absolutely awesome.

By the way, push open the right side of the entrance door to enter since the left side is locked.

Octopus SHISHLIK! is simplicity at its best. The briny sweetness of grilled tender meaty octopus tentacle is accentuated by the simple addition of olive oil, lemon and herbs. Highly recommended.

Tiger Prawns wrapped in tomato seeds butter is another awesome dish of Miznon though it is only in the dinner menu. The prawns are so succulent, briny sweet with firm flesh. "Wrapped in tomato seeds butter", the extra light warm zest with richness of butter makes the prawns taste even better.

Every ribbon of fresh blue crab pasta is coated with the buttery briny flavour of crab. I’m really surprised by how flavourful and rich this seemingly plain looking pasta is. And hidden beneath the pasta is a huge mould of fresh, silky crab meat.

Grilled Calamari resting in a potato with sour cream and herbs is love at first bite. Yes, with that first bite, I'm spellbound by the light briny goodness with zest, savoury taste, pungency of herbs, tangy creaminess of sour cream and earthy starchiness of potato.

The complimentary bread served at dinner is of another level as compared to its lunch counterpart. I can say it is worth it to specially come here for this bread. The special flatbread here has a delightful slightly chewy texture and is so unique in flavour,. Topped with sliced tomato and green chilli, the bread is full of exotic tastes, and this is amped up even more by the cilantro sauce paired with sour cream.

Naked Chocolate Cake is full of rich, luscious goodness of chocolate with a lovely crispy top and tastes nice, but kind of ordinary and not really memorable.

NOTE: Desserts at dinner is a totally different beast! Lots of selection and the Mango Malabi is insanely good. It is actually panna cotta in Israeli style. The pudding is so milky, smooth and silky. I love it.

Thoughts: Israeli Cuisine is now in my list of favourites!

I’m glad to try the Israel food with its unique cook with fresh ingredients.
The juicy kebab really juicy, hummus prawn is so delicious, the pasta a bit too plain and sour for me.
With its music in the background, it’s nice to dine with some alcohol, the cocktail tastes just right!

My husband and I really love the food here. We had hummus with prawns, burratta, figs and the focaccia. The figs were served with bourgogne cheese and olive oil, they blended very well. The service here was also very good. Would like to come back here to try the other dishes. Perfect place for date night or dinner with friends.

adr_address: 72 Amoy St, Singapore 069891
name: Nouri

reviews.text: Food are nice and tasty. Lunch meal items are fixed and so is the set lunch. Prices are quite okay for Michelin but need to book in advanced. Food plating looks beautiful. Ambience are good too. Service is good and so is the serving time.

Lots of interesting stuff to try here. A beautifully paced tasting menu consisting of really elaborate dishes with layers and layers of flavors you can dive in. Seriously exciting stuff and every dish has some reading to go with it in case you come solo like I did and want to learn more of the back story.
Great service too, hats off to chef and the team

Food was great, service was great, atmosphere was great. It was relaxed and we had a good time over good food. All the options were presented to us so well; tea, opening drinks, etc. I was just slightly shocked that the selection of tea to end the meal costed $30ish per pot. But other than that, I enjoyed dinner.

An exceptional experience, very fortunate to have visited this unique restaurant last night. These folks have real flair, making the visit enjoyable from the moment we arrived. I think that I can relate to the chefs “cross roads” concept, an amazing set menu with elements from across the globe. Great wine pairing, loved hearing the story lines.  Loved the casual, relaxed atmosphere. Everything presented with confidence and fun.  Well deserving of its Michelin status.  Each course was remarkable, but I was particularly taken with the chocolate fish ball!

The owner did a wonderful service. We went in for lunch before our flight and the service was prompt and the food came out in a nice pace for lunch. The food was ok and this is my second time here. It has been consistent during the years. This is a nice spot to bring business guest for lunch as it is usually quiet during lunch in the area where most of the comparable restaurants may only open for dinner.  Yes, it is quite pricey.

adr_address: 60 Collyer Quay, Singapore 049322
name: OUE Tower

reviews.text: OUE Tower impresses with its sleek design and panoramic views of the cityscape. The modern architecture blends seamlessly with state-of-the-art facilities. The vibrant atmosphere, coupled with excellent amenities, creates a dynamic workplace. A landmark for both business and leisure, OUE Tower stands tall as a symbol of urban sophistication.

OUE Tower is an office building, home to the corporate division of the Bank of America. A separate building beside it houses Tong. Le private dining restaurant. The only revolving restaurant in Singapore. Surrounding area nearby with eateries and the Bayfront hotel, makes it a pleasant place for a leisurely stroll along the waterfront.
Prominently situated along the shoreline of Collyer Quay. Formerly known as Change Alley Aerial Tower. Tóng Lè Private Dining, located on its revolving tower, offers exquisite Chinese cuisine.

This is a pretty nice building - yes, it rotates, and occasionally you can even feel the ground shudder. If you like that sort of thing, it can be fun. It's in a very nice location in the heart of Singapore and has excellent views of the city all the way around.
Nice tower with proximity to town area. Clean and well maintained building.

adr_address: 88 Market St, #51-01, Singapore 048948
name: OUMI Modern Japanese Kappo Restaurant

reviews.text:
Keisha has been most hospitable to us. Always attentive to our needs.
Chef Xinyi is very sincere and takes a lot of pride in her work. Love her detailed explanation of the ingredients used and the cooking techniques behind each dish.
Executive Chef Lamley is very impressive with his knife skills and culinary technique. Food is really delicious and the presentation is first class!

We started off the meal with some sashimis before moving into the mains (Buta Kakuni, Shio Koji Teppan, Gindara Misoyaki) and Chirashi bowls. The portion were just nice as we got the individual mains to share! Really enjoyed the black cod fish grilled to perfection! And we ended off with the desserts (Kyoho Sorbet, Yoghurt Lychee Sake Sorbet & Yuzu) which tasted as well as how it's beautifully plated! Enjoyed the ambience with an amazing city view from L51 together with great companions! Thank you to the service staff for being patient and recommended items for us to get! Highly recommended if you'll like an intimate spot with a good treat! 😍💯

Momotaro Cheese
- Started dinner with this. Unique balanced flavours of sweet, tart, savoury, and a brightness from the fennel flower coming through with nice texture contrast from the crunch of the nori rice puffs. Really nice start.

Sashimi Momiji
- Before the sashimi was served, each guest will get a plate of soy sauce placed in front of them and its fragrance just wafts up in a form of a warm greeting. Sashimi Momiji platter came with a surprise mini show (shall not spoil it!). Each sashimi was skilfully sliced and really fresh. Favourite is the Botan Ebi Sashimi.

Foie Gras Monaka
- So indulgent, a little messy, but once again so balanced and really yummy. Presentation was also beautiful with flowers from the Arden Food Forest.

Tempura Crepe
- A fresh take on tempura. Light and lots of pops of different flavours. Really delicate plating. Once again a hit!

Wagyu Teppanyaki
- Cooked to perfection, paired beautifully with the sauce (which thankfully was not doused over the meat), really appreciated the cut used as Wagyu tends to get a little too “fatty” for my personal taste so with the striploin we got a better balance of meat and fat. The Aomori Garlic adds smokiness and so much depth to the overall dish. Yums!

Shio Koji Teppan Chicken
- Chicken was so tender and the house made curry sauce was fragrant but yet still delicate and not too overpowering/strong/heavy. Small note was that a skin started to form on the sauce but that doesn’t affect much overall.

Gindara Misoyaki
- Nice char, Gindara was lightly sweet and practically melts in your mouth. One of the favourites of the night.

Somen
- Very light, warm and comforting. Noodle texture was so smooth, would’ve slurped it all up without stopping if I wasn’t full to brim already.

Yoghurt Lychee Sake Sorbet
- Perfect ending to the meal. Really interesting Shisho veil that’s very light and bouncy, goes very well with all the other components to cleanse the palate and end on a very refreshing note.

Overall, a very good meal. My family and I enjoyed everything very much and were very full. Amazing food complimented with a beautiful view of the city. Service by the whole team was amazing. Left the ordering of the dishes to Keisha and the order and dishes chosen were perfect. Highly recommend!

TL:DR Exquisite food that is chockful of flavour yet nuanced, in an intimate setting complemented by an exceptional view (over MBS no less). A must try!

Had the omakase dinner with my partner to celebrate a special occasion, and if I’m being honest, also to splurge on ourselves a little and look after our mental well-being. Executive Chef Lamley helms this team of well-drilled chefs where everyone diligently went about their tasks which produced the excellent meal we had.

The first course was Kabocha Uni Tofu which consists of their home-made tofu, pumpkin, Shiitake Tsuyu, and the ever craved after ‘gold of the sea’ – Uni or Sea Urchin. Light, refreshing (a bit on the sweet side due to the pumpkin) but a great start to the meal.

The second course and probably the most visually stunning and IG worthy was the Hassun which is an assortment of small dishes, placed on a bed of sea salt and adorned with ornaments that would not be out of place in a Japanese garden. We had four dishes, all of which were delicious and memorable. The most unique was probably a special tomato that was dressed in a wasabi sauce that still had kick but was not overwhelming, possibly tempered by the cheese and crispy rice-pops, and as a whole was something I had not eaten before. The other dish that I should probably mention is the mushroom that tasted exactly like Abalone! Do note that these dishes would likely change from time to time depending on seasonality (I guess).

The third course was an assortment of five types of sashimi, all of which were fresh and tasty. If you are willing to invest a bit more in this experience, you could consider adding the ‘Assorted Sashimi’ which we did. Feel free to speak with the chefs about this. If available, I highly recommend the smoked chutoro which as I type, I am still pining after. The chef smokes the fatty tuna in a claypot of sorts which gives it a rich, smoky flavour. In my conversation with the chef, I complimented him on this dish, particularly on its balance. He mentioned that smoking it and maintaining the balance was only possible because of its fat content which prevents it from becoming dry.

The fourth course was the Foie Gras Monaka. I usually feel quite jelak from having foie gras but how this was executed was perfect and I actually wished there was more. The foie gras is made into a ganache, and contrasted with salmon roe, shiso and encased within two crisp wafers. Exceptional!

The other three courses consist of a soup (we had the cod fish soup), a main – there was a choice of either Buta Kakuni (pork) or Shio Koji Teppan Chicken – as well as a dessert (Kyoho Sorbet). All were on point and every morsel was a delight. The attention to detail probably stands out. For example, the cod fish soup could have been just good but the umami of the skin elevated the dish; when asked, the chef indicated that they marinated the skin to enhance the flavour. The combination of tastes that our minds may not fathom going well together, like grape (Kyoho) and black sesame, but which sang in harmony on our tastebuds also expanded our culinary minds and enhanced our experience.

Do wash down all that lovely food with some of their sake. We were feeling a bit adventurous so we tried the Tenryohomare Karakuchi Ginjo which was said to have a light spicy note (it was very smooth and we loved it), but you can stick with their (according to the waitress) popular Toko Junmai Ginjo Genshu which has melon and pear notes. You get to choose your own sake cup too!

Last, enjoy the view! Come for the first sitting at 6pm so that you get to witness the sunset and the Singapore skyscape transform into a canopy of dazzling lights.

Can’t wait to go back again!

No doubt the place is something you would visit with the stunning view of MBS , other than that the food is nothing special although there are many choices for their Saturday bruch and you can order as much as you can. I would commend though the pork belly, sword fish sashimi, and tuna sushi. While for dessert,  the yuzu and mandarin lamington are a must to try and beware, you might ask for 2nd round.

Overall, the lunch experience was good but price is on the high side. It would be good if brunch includes at least a choice for a cup of coffee or tea to complete your meal.

adr_address: 1 St Andrew's Rd, #01-04 National Gallery, Singapore 178957

editorial_summary.overview: Modern French cuisine served amid sophisticated decor in the National Gallery Singapore.

formatted_address: 1 St Andrew's Rd, #01-04 National Gallery, Singapore 178957
name: Odette

reviews.text: Had lunch here and got wonderful experience. Relaxing atmosphere with subtle service that provides great tempo of serving food. Wine selection is impressive. All dishes are delicious and display is unique. Highly recommend. Only one thing about desert, maybe can add more creativity to make a fabulous end.

I had the pleasure of celebrating my 20th anniversary at Odette and it was an exquisite culinary experience. The ambiance exuded elegant sophistication creating a perfect setting for an indulgent evening. The menu showcased a masterful blend of French flavors with innovative twists, each dish a testament to the chef's culinary artistry and showmanship. Impeccable presentation, attentive service, and a carefully curated wine list further elevated the dining experience. This restaurant is truly deserving of their 3 Michelin stars and World’s Best restaurant accolades.

At a price point of $650 per pax (Epicure; dinner) including 1 glass of champagne, I would expect to be absolutely blown away.

Service, food, ambience whilst great was not a $650/pax kinda great. Probably exceeds expectations at $400/pax.

Food: Expected 7 courses but there was a number of starters and desserts which was a pleasant surprise! Was full by the first course. Enjoyed all the dishes other than the pigeon which was too gamey for my liking and couldn’t finish half of it. Wasn’t particularly wowed by any of the dishes (unlike at Gaggan’s where I was really impressed by how innovative the dishes were) but was delighted by the gift at the end cos it was an unexpected touch

Service: was fun, welcoming, relaxing but not as polished as I’d expect a 3 Michelin service to be.

Ambience: felt like the location in National gallery removed the lush factor. Had to get through throngs of people / messy spaces to get to the restaurant. Restrooms were also not nearby. Would recommend only if one has cash to spare and wants to give this famous brand a try.

Great place and team, I got presented with a labeled jam as a gift at the end of the night. The total bill ended up being S$1254 for two people (Epicure Menu), which is a lot by all means, but given the 3-star rating and the fame of the restaurant, it is worth visiting if you have the chance!

Deserves a three-stars... on Google
The welcome snacks were decent, but nothing outstanding. The donut seemed average and greasy, while the impromptu shrimp taco was good, and the onion tart was delightful.
The following appetizer, mushroom tea - a mushroom soup infused with truffle, offered a rich and dense mushroom broth with the essence of truffle - was delicious, akin to immersing oneself in a forest basket full of mushrooms.
The first course composed of sea urchin caviar and black caviar with mousse and shrimp. Since I initially warned that I did not like sea urchin caviar, they replaced the dish from black caviar to crab accompanied by apple and avocado. The crab taste was overshadowed by the apples, making it an inadequate substitute for black caviar in both price and flavor. I told the waiter about this, he offered to bring me this dish with caviar, but then he conveniently forgot about me.
Their renowned signature egg dish, featuring yolk, potato mousse, and chorizo, presented a good blend of raw yolk with salty chorizo and soft potatoes. However, the inadequate amount of chorizo left one with only a regular yolk in the end, which was rather disappointing.
For an additional $100, my husband upgraded the dish to langoustines with truffle generously sprinkled, creating a delicious and harmonious blend of flavors. It seems that to enjoy something truly tasty at this restaurant, one must be prepared to pay extra.
The fish crudo course with dill received no complaints, while the scallop with chicory was flavorful but somewhat simplistic, not quite fitting for a three-star establishment.
Now, onto the most disappointing aspect - the main signature dish. The medium-rare roasted pigeon had a peculiar taste reminiscent of offal, with a slightly strange smell. This type of meat may not appeal to everyone, making its presence on the menu somewhat odd. We expressed our dissatisfaction with the dish to the waiter.
We were offered chicken as a replacement, which turned out to be simple chicken sous vide lacking any distinctive flavor or complexity. At $490 on the menu, this dish felt uninspired. The waiter suggested an alternative - foie gras with abalone broth, which proved more intriguing than the previous dishes but failed to deliver a phenomenal taste.
Visiting a restaurant with a three-star rating, we expected surprises, unique culinary experiences, and intriguing flavor combinations to expand our palate. However, all the dishes at this establishment seemed basic, using common ingredients readily found in any restaurant. Singapore boasts a high standard of dining establishments, making it perplexing how this restaurant attained three stars; having visited over 15 Michelin-starred venues worldwide, we would rate this at most one star due to the lack of innovative solutions, interesting flavor pairings, or premium ingredients. Though some dishes showcased creative techniques, it was insufficient.
Desserts were unremarkable, merely sweet cakes lacking balance or contrasting flavors to offset the sweetness.
Service
The service was inattentive, with dirty dishes left unattended on the table until a new dish was served.
To sum up:
Drawing from my extensive experience dining at Michelin-starred establishments, I can conclude that:
- Service falls short of high standards
- They don’t have their own toilet, only a shared one in the gallery, it takes 3 minutes to walk, where the cabins were found to be unclean.
- The cuisine is simplistic, lacking fascinating flavor combinations, textures, or premium ingredients. Despite the $490 set menu price, the offering fails to reflect the expected quality.
If you have visited most Michelin-starred restaurants in Singapore, a visit could be considered; however, if not, we do not recommend it. There are other establishments more deserving of your attention.

adr_address: 55 Keong Saik Rd., #01-03, Singapore 089158
name: Olivia Restaurant & Lounge

reviews.text:
We had very good dinner here and it was one of the unforgettable ones. The hosts gave very good recommendations, from the appetizers down to the wine selection to go with our meal. The olives appetizers were exquisite. Every course after that was layered with different complementing flavours and textures. My favourite main dish was the beef. It was perfectly cooked and juicy down to the bones. The highlight of the day was definitely the cheese cake. This is a must order for anyone visiting the restaurant. It is so creamy and literally just melts with every spoon in your mouth. Just perfect.

Service was tip top and responsive. Great recommendations from the hosts. Really awesome environment for an evening out with friends and family.

[26/02/24]

Pic 1: Cheesecake - 10/10 Definitely a must-try when coming here. It's a very unique cheesecake and I think words aren't sufficient to describe it

Pic 2: Beef cheek with potato - 8/10 Beef cheek was super tender and potato complemented it well. I felt it was slightly on the salty side though

Pic 3: Octopus + braised pork with potato foam 8/10 - Braised pork was heavenly and the octopus was super soft. Again, octopus felt a bit too salty but you can try it and decide for yourself

Pic 4: Croquettes 10/10 and the lobster starter 8/10 (sorry forgot the exact name). Croquettes were super nice and crispy on the outside and loaded + soft on the inside. Lobster is very nice and fresh.

Service: Service was great and servers were very friendly and attentive!

Atmosphere: Interior and decor of the restaurant is cosy and the open kitchen concept (I think) is quite interesting. It was quite heartwarming to see the chefs being friendly with each other too

Dinner was great, we had the 6.30pm seating and the staff was really nice to make some arrangement to allow us to stay longer. All the dishes we ordered was great especially love the black rice and lamb rack. Gambas was different from the usually, secretly wishes the prawns were bigger. Of course we had to have the cheese cake for dessert no matter how full you are. The wine selection was great, with good recommendation from the host. The only feedback I might give is if the music can be slightly softer (except when the suckling pig is out, really enjoyed the festivity for that). Thanks for looking out for us during our dinner. Much enjoyable from everyone.

Came here for lunch on a weekend. Atmosphere was great and staff were really attentive and friendly throughout. Have to recommend the Octopus/Pork Belly as well as the Beef Cheeks! Their famous cheesecake is super unique and delicious too! Overall a fantastic dining experience with bold and strong flavours.

We had dinner here on a Fri evening to celebrate our wedding anniversary. The staff was friendly and guided us so that we did not over/under order. We had grilled eggplant and truffle mushroom croquettes for starts. Prawns and beef cheeks for seconds and then shared small pasta with scallops. All the food is good. The prawns were tops if we had to ranked the items. The piped music was quite loud. We are very thankful that we could get a spot for 2 at the counter without reservations at peak dinner time Fri evening. As we were seated side by side each other at the counter so we could chat easily, notwithstanding the loud music. Watching the chefs prepare and cook at their stations was interesting, too.

adr_address: 333 Orchard Rd, Level 5, Singapore 238867
name: Osteria Mozza

reviews.text:
Sat on the semi outdoor dinning area on a super hot day. The ambience is actually quite nice but it was not comfortable dinning experience at this price range.

The food quality is decent but slightly under delivered. Worst bite being the chewy octopus starter. Best bite being the lamb shank that pulls apart in the nice tomato glaze. The deconstructed Caesar salad is interesting but I actually wanted some vegetables and there’s like 4 leaves. The steak has a nice crust but not the tenderness I’d associate with wagyu.

Food: Enjoyed the caprese and the crispy potato but it’s not that outstanding for me to return. It was just ok. I ordered the raviolo stuffed with ricotta and egg, again, it was fine but I wouldn’t go back there for this dish. It was just alright. They do not allow you to cut a birthday cake bought from outside and as it was my birthday this was a bit disappointing. However, they did give us a sorbet for free and took a Polaroid.

Service: We were seated at a table and waited for 15 minutes before having to flag down a wait staff. The restaurant was busy but not overwhelmingly so and there were many free wait staff who just ignored our table while serving the table next to us, who arrived later. After the drink was served, we had to wait another 10 minutes before somebody came to take our order.

Ambience: didn’t really enjoy the vibe of the place. We were given a table that was near the connecting door to the outdoor seating area, this despite there being several empty tables elsewhere. Probably should have asked them to change the tables as it was distracting that one of us constantly had somebody going and coming next to them, as they were sat next to the door. The design of the restaurant too is a bit baffling cause it doesn’t remind me of Italy and somehow just seems clumsy and a generic western. To add on, somehow there’s a heavy smokiness in the air that just feels grimy. Over all I didn’t find this living up to its upmarket status. Seemed a bit gritty with mediocre food. We didn’t have the wine, but got served severely watered down Italian sodas.

Overall, I would not return to there because staff, food and ambience don’t really appeal to me.

Went for the special one night collaboration with Burnt Ends and it was amazing. Hearty Italian meets intense BBQ is such a great combination that I am itching to try Nancy's food on its own immediately after the dinner. Will be back !

Celebrated a friend’s birthday over here. Vibes were immaculate especially the outdoor-enclosed section.

Excellent service and great food, but perhaps missing just that extra oomph that would bump this up to a 5-star rating, given the price point of the restaurant. Dishes were great but perhaps not enough to warrant a second visit.

Just a side note that the restaurant doesn’t allow birthday cakes (bought from outside) to be eaten in the restaurant 🥲

During my recent visit to Osteria Mozza, housed within a reputed 5-star hotel, my dining experience fell short of expectations. The ambiance was elegant, in line with the hotel's prestige. However, I found the food to be mediocre, lacking the anticipated finesse. The limited menu options didn't offer a diverse culinary experience, leaving much to be desired. Considering its affiliation with a luxury hotel, I had anticipated a higher standard in terms of food quality and variety. Regrettably, the dishes presented were underwhelming, failing to meet the expected level of sophistication and flavor. While the ambiance reflected sophistication, the gastronomic aspect left room for significant improvement. Enhancing the menu diversity and elevating the culinary standards could better align Osteria Mozza with the esteemed status of its hosting 5-star establishment. $$$+

adr_address: 127 Kitchener Rd, Singapore 208514
name: PUTIEN Kitchener Road

reviews.text:
Located in a shop house interior is air- conditioned.
Dining areas are compartmentalised with 3-4 table in each area  which is good to avoid overcrowding. Interior a Tad bit on the cold side .

Ah Lian  the server was warm and excellent with dish recommendations

Bitter Goude- excellent, had the seeds which have a rather crunchy texture , the sauce rather thick like it was thickened with corn starch.

The ginger duck was excellent- some of the meat had the skin on it.

The bean curd in sauce was also excellent. Complex taste of the sauce like it was mushroom or soybean broth.

The seafood noodles was the weakest dish that we tried - it was overly thick sauce which was blend. The seafood was sloshy on the chewy side.

Service was excellent by Ah Lian.
First try Putien restaurant! Is really damn delicious! Most of the dishes is nice and will come back again
Yummy food as usual. Love so many dishes here! Uploading pics of a few now

Wish we would have come another day. Had a booking for Monday (ahead of the lunar new year). Were only offered a lunar set menu with two options for two people. No other menu / dishes were offered. Also drinks menu was significantly reduced. After visiting loads of Michelin starred places around the globe, one to three, just judging by our experience, I wouldn’t know where the star comes from. Dishes weren’t special, way too similar. All soupy and not really flavourful. The ingredients may have been special for the main pot dish but taste wise, not my cup of tea. Also, and I rarely say that, was too much food for two people. Service was friendly but no one spoke English.

Food - Ordered the season specials - oysters in seaweed and claypot basil braised oysters. They were delicious and fresh! The signature HingHua Lor Mee did not disappoint with light delicate flavours. The noodles were soft and silky and still had good bite.For those looking for strong and tasty food, this is not your place. The desserts were just heavenly. So light and delicate and a great way to finish off a meal. Try them all. The Orr Nee was so smooth and delicate.

Service and atmosphere - very friendly and efficient service. Special thanks to Ah Lian (莲姐）who made our dining experience so pleasant. She recommended great dishes for us to try and suggested just enough to fill us without being pushy.

adr_address: 30 Boat Quay, Singapore 049819
name: Pasta Fresca Da Salvatore (Boat Quay)

reviews.text: Located in the charming Boat Quay area, this Italian restaurant is very much worth visiting. For a quiet atmosphere, I recommend sitting indoors. My experience was during the last order, so the restaurant was peaceful with quick service. The dishes we ordered were all expertly prepared and absolutely delicious. The burrata was a standout, truly delightful! One of the highlights of dining here is the ability to customize your pasta to your liking. Overall, a great spot for a satisfying Italian meal.

Vongole had generous amount of clams. Arrabiata had a nice spicy kick which was perfect for us. The beef salami pizza had thin crispy crust which was so delightful.

The ambiance at the outdoor area, by the river, is perfect for a special date night.

The Arancini Di Riso and Alla Carbonara is amazing, very nice and delicious.

For the Prosciutto E Funghi was not bad but can be improved (:

A hidden gem. The staff (I think he is the owner) was so good. He is very social and offered two types of special chillies for us. Good selection of vegetarian food. Aglio Olio was awesome, homemade ice lemon tea was great, Margherita pizza was lovely. Chilli pickle in olive oil was super.

Classy Italian restaurant at boat quay. Huge variety of pasta in the menu, but unfortunately I'm no connoisseur and was a bit stumped. Waiter was really friendly, and didn't judge or advise when I picked a questionable combination of carbonara with spinach ravioli...unable to judge pasta quality fairly. Though frankly I was surprised at how creamy and gao the carbonara sauce was, was expecting the authentic egg yolk kind of sauce?

Lesson learnt, not to anyhow mix and match.

adr_address: 12 Marina Boulevard, Tower 3, #01-05/06 Marina Bay Financial Centre, Singapore 018982
formatted_address: 12 Marina Boulevard, Tower 3, #01-05/06 Marina Bay Financial Centre, Singapore 018982
name: Path Restaurant

reviews.text: Path was the best dining experience I'd had in months. There was such creativity in each dish, they were all standout and tasteful. The bread spread was chilli crab with beancurd and uni, the chicken rice had neither chicken nor rice, the abalone was just delicious and I can't believe I've never had frozen overripe persimmon. Our waitress Moni was attentive and helpful, she was passionate about her explanation of each dish. I highly recommend having dinner here!

Had a team dinner and they specially curated the menu for us, right down to our individual dietary requirements.

Service and food were impeccable and the food was delicious!

Came for restaurant week lunch, and was quite surprised as food served was very fusion
Started off with a sea bream and hairy crab roe. Sea bream dish shocked us as they added hainanese sauce which reminds me of the chicken dish. The onsen egg duck was pretty good and so was the blue cod: dessert (water mochi) was fairly normal , mostly tasted jelly.
Was 98$++ which came to just below 120
Service was very good and close to fine dine levels. Sth good for try for once..
Clean and balanced dishes at Path. Thanks Chef Marvas and team. Moni young and nice front of house. Keep it up guys.

Lunch at Path Restaurant and tried their new menu and it was awesome. We were a little sad to see the well loved set lunch menu no longer available but were not disappointed with the new menu. For this season they have some East-West inspired dishes with emphasis on seafood. The menu while big but was well proportioned so light eaters will be able to complete. A very well valued meal and worth to try.

editorial_summary.overview: German comfort fare & beers served in a bustling, high-ceilinged pub with outdoor seating.

name: Paulaner Bräuhaus Singapore

reviews.text:
It is always a great place for weekend brunch or a la carte dinner. It was also once a great place for their lunch promotions. Unfortunately, this has changed a bit, portions got considerably small and prices went up.
Would surely continue to go for brunch and dinner but will be skipping lunch.
No doubts about the service, always been great.
A great place for German Food and Beer. Servers are very friendly and attentive to your needs and enquiries about the dishes. Also gave a complimentary birthday dish as well!

Came here with my two kids (4 and 2) and the in laws for Sunday brunch, and the experience was perfect as it always has been! Great service, super accommodative service especially to the kids, and of course the amazing food! Tender pork knuckle with super crispy skin, perfectly roasted beef, and of course the best schnitzel in town. This is our favourite haunt and can’t stop recommending it enough.

Special shoutout to Rana, Vincent, David and Dennis for making this experience perfect 👌 we will be back for sure

1st visit to experience the Oktoberfest here. The band was very entertaining and we had good fun. Crowd that night was spontaneous.

The Oktoberfest beer is light and smooth. Non alcoholic Weissbier beer suits friends who can't drink.

Music is a little way too loud, though, especially if seated in front of the band.
Fantastic dining & drinking with supplier here. Good beer, good food, good service. Clean and spacious. It’s gonna be our company, colleagues and inbound visitors new chill out place.

adr_address: 1 Nanson Rd, Singapore 238909

editorial_summary.overview: Italian cuisine & handcrafted cocktails served in a trendy setting with rustic, contemporary decor.

name: Publico Ristorante

reviews.text: Amazing food. Amazing service. Amazing ambiance. Our sever Sakthi was the best—she was friendly, welcoming, and extremely customer oriented; talking to her felt like talking to a friend. Yet, she remained super professional throughout, recommending us dishes and making casual conversation. Overall 100/10 dining experience.

Vibrant and chic ambience perfect for a night catch up with friends or family. They have both indoor and outdoor seating so you get to choose whether you want some air conditioning or fresh air setting. The view from this restaurant is very relaxing. Although the food price is not cheap but the taste were spot on. I love the pizza, it was my favourite out of what we have ordered.

Everything we ordered was great. The beef ribs and pork chops was the best for us! The breaded chicken was good with a generous portion!

The pizza crust was really thin too.

Will def come again :)

Complimentary tiramisu if you pay with Citibank 💳

Restaurant got both indoor and outdoor dining area depending on the type of experience we want. But obviously indoor will be the most preference.

The crew are quite attentive and responsive with their standard professional reply 😂 eg: we checked on our pasta and one said there are long order queue and the another one served the pasta 10seconds right after. We loved their speedy food preparation and serving just that the first crew member don’t even check and told us about the long order list reason. Crew team/supervisors/managers are caring.

Octopus is slightly too chewy at the thicker tentacle parts. Steak came with quite a number of tendons in almost 50% of the cutlets. Pork collar dressing is a bit “jelak”. The rest are good!

We loved their pizza and pasta on top of the rest. Crispy dough and tender pasta are the best parts for the kids.

Tiramisu has strong rum flavour we loved it so much too, just the portion might be abit smaller 😂. Chocolate brownie is standard sweet dessert, sweet lover will definitely love it.

Overall we had a chill and happy dinner time at the restaurant.

Our favourite Italian rest. We always go to this rest when we crave for pizza. Best pizza we had in SG. Service is brilliant. Well trained and friendly staff. Nice atmosphere. Kids friendly. Comfortable to sit outside and enjoy the riverside.

adr_address: 5 Wallich St, #01-16, Singapore 078883
name: Pura Brasa Singapore

reviews.text:
Had a really pleasant experience here, food, service, vibe, everything was excellent. The meats were all grilled to perfection with a nice charcoal flavour. The pork ribs were literally fall off the bone tender and full of flavour even without dipping any sauces, i would say it’s the best ribs i’ve eaten, and it’s really filling. Octopus was also phenomenal.

The service here is amazing, Micky was friendly and entertaining. The indoor seating vibe is really nice and unique. 10/10 would come back again 👍

Nice Atmosphere, Great Service

This place has a nice atmosphere outdoors in the evening when it’s cooler. The service deserves special mention though.

Had dinner with friends on a weekday evening. It was quite busy but the service was amazing. They take special care to make sure you have everything you need even before you ask for it. When my pizza was served, a few of us were not at the table. When we returned and started on the pizza, the service staff came immediately to the table to ask if wanted any chilli flakes/tabasco to go with it. Just exactly what I wanted.

Food was good as well. Prices are reasonable for a place in the downtown core.

The outside seating had a pleasant ambience of not being too quiet not crowded. Lighting was adequate and service staff well within reach.

Anyone who wants to have an enjoyable meal with great service should come to this place.

This was a pretty good restaurant for a gathering! The seafood paella, pizza and grilled squid (loved the accompanying truffle mash!) were all good but what really stood out was the grilled pork belly, which melted in the mouth.

Service is warm and friendly, and the food was served fast. This is a nice place to eat, drink and chill the night away with friends.

It was my 1st visit, and I really enjoyed the atmosphere. The staff are so friendly attentive and fun-loving. Really enjoyed eating in a happy environment, especially this is my birthday dinner. One of the in charge is Micky, who is humorous and generous.. Thank you for the birthday cake. Definitely will come back again. Thank you my friend Calin for recommending this place.. she had been here for 5 times!

We ordered pork ribs and seafood paella.

Fast & efficient service: The food was served less than 30 minutes from when we placed the order.

Food: pork ribs was soft, melts in your mouth. The serving is also generous.

Ambiance: perfect for Friday night hangout

Kenken was very friendly as well!

adr_address: 6 Eu Tong Sen St, #02-72 to 75/77/92 The Central, Singapore 059817
formatted_address: 6 Eu Tong Sen St, #02-72 to 75/77/92 The Central, Singapore 059817
name: Rendezvous Restaurant Hock Lock Kee

reviews.text:
chicken were juicy and tender, sotong was well cooked as well, however the beef was overcooked and tough. curry were flavourful and thick.

as many have mentioned, food might not be served piping hot as ingredients were cooked and chopped up separately before the hot curry was added.

My childhood favourite eating place - when they were at the original Rendezvous Hotel at Bras Basah Rd.
All the food brings back so much good memories.
Brought my parents to eat and my father remembered eating there when he was a teenager in the 60s

One of my favourite Restaurants in Singapore.

Rendevouz was originally located along Bras Basah Road where the current Rendevouz Hotel is today.

It was called Rendevouz because thats the place to meet before or after a movie in Cathay Cinema across the road.

Rendevouz was famous for its "Nasi Padang".

But really, I would not call Rendevouz food Indonesian Cuisine.

Rendevouz serves essentially SINGAPORE CUISINE.

Their curries, chillies and dishes are all a blend of Indonesian, Indian, Malay, Pernankan and Chinese cuisines, honed through time tested experience from satisfying the Singaporean palate for over 50yrs.

Thats why as a Singaporean, I love the food here. Its uniquely Singapore.

Almost Every dish is a must try.

If you can take spicy, try the sambal egg plant and sambal Sotong.  If you cannot take spicy, the Ayam Goreng and Ayam Lemak is good, as well as nonya chap chye and Begedile.

Beef Rendang is also excellent.

They also serve traditional malay deserts like Chendol.

Its a restaurant I alway look forward to visit.

Long time since I ate here. Food still tasted  amazing, although in my opinion, it was slightly better in the early years. Kroma chicken and the sayur lodeh were amazing. The beef rendang is not as tender as I like it to be but still very good. The squid is yummy and has good value for money. Overall, I was really satisfied with my meal today.

I'm here to share my disappointment about revisiting a place I used to enjoy for its nostalgia and food. Unfortunately, the quality of the food has noticeably declined, and the service was subpar. Upon entering, no staff approached us, so we approached a young gentleman to request a table for two. We were instructed to place our orders at the counter before being seated. To top it off, the food arrived cold and lacked the flavorful and spicy taste I remembered. I ordered a hot "kopi o kosong," but they served me an iced version by mistake. Despite my dissatisfaction, I didn't want to spoil the atmosphere and accepted it. Overall, I believe they could improve both their service and food quality. It's unlikely I'll return, especially considering the anticipated premium prices due to the location.

name: Restaurant Euphoria

reviews.text: I echo some reviews below. While the concept of drawing inspiration from the onion was interesting, the execution fell short. Although the dishes were beautifully presented and well executed, we found the flavors a bit repetitive and left us wanting for more (flavours). We still had a very enjoyable night in overall.

Had a very euphoric birthday celebration here with my boyfriend! Don’t be put off by the fact that the menu is centered around onions; they use Cévennes onions that are unbelievably sweet and taste more like a crunchy vegetable than the usual pungent bulb that we know and love (or hate)!

There were so many courses that I’d be hard pressed to describe each one. But generally we loved:
- The use of the thin filo pastry which in itself comprised many layers!!
- how thinly sliced some things were, a true testament to a chef’s skill!
- how each dish had a fruity element to it (be it with a touch of grapes, pear, oranges etc)

The highlight for us was of course “my favourite vegetable”. My boyfriend would not get enough of the earl grey “onion tea” whereas I preferred the onion cup of onion puree, truffle and a sousvide egg! And yes, we did eat the inner layer of the onion bowl and we enjoyed it.

Their rendition of the Yorkshire pudding also took us by surprise. It was like a fluffy candle crisp on the outside that held its own apart from being a vehicle for the custard.

Yet another notable part of the experience was picking the Damascus steel knife of our choosing before tucking into the pork jowl. Yes, a little dramatic but it was fun and we got to marvel at the beautiful texture of the steel for a bit.

The desserts were almost a whole different omakase on its own. Everything was spectacular in its own way. The iced kiwi thing with the mint sorbet and almonds was a much needed refreshing palate cleanser after tasting all the various onion reductions. The topsy-turvy mont blanc was so so unique whilst still retaining its chest nutty goodness. And the dessert box! That really stole the show.

If I must critique something, it would be that the various jus-es and reductions felt too heavy after a while, especially by the last meat item. I appreciate the effort and ingredients put into creating each flavorful sauce but having it more spread out would be nice!

All in all a great dinner and the servers were lovely as well.

Had their valentines set menu the day before valentines. I would say the food was executed in an acceptable manner in terms of flavor balance, texture, and preparation technique. Service felt a little rushed with explanations of the food delivered like I was watching a YouTube video at 2x speed. Ambiance of the restaurant was well thought out however the plants inside the restaurant were all plastic, calling themselves Gastro Botanical 2.0 and yet filling the place with fake plants really was a disappointment. However the biggest let down was the lack of story telling and cohesion with the food from the 4th plate and onwards.. The first 3 had a story about the chef and his love for onions, then things really went off the rails when they presented Brazilian cheese bread as mochi bread without the soul of the bread and some form of French onion soup reduction. After that the meals were all confusing flavors that had no ties to gastro botanical story or onions. Overall I was expecting a 3 part narrative but was only delivered the first part and the remaining parts just meandered around in my taste buds without rhyme or reason

All the dishes were beautifully presented, but overall the flavor profiles lacked a little depth and soul. And while I really appreciated the story and theme of inspirations from the humble yet lovely onion that carried from one dish to the next, somehow it didn’t quite hit for me. It wasn’t a harmonious cohesion between the concept and following execution. It felt like, we were peeling away the layers of an onion, and instead of discovering something unexpected and surreal, or even euphoric, I found exactly what I’d expect to find at the center, more onion. Also the service was a little hit and miss. One dish was served with 3 food elements but 1 of them came later than the other two and that felt a bit of an amateur mistake. Absolutely understandable that it can happen and it’s no big deal to me, but the fix or solution could’ve been handled better and with more finesse

Food
* Accompanying sauces take centre stage dominating dishes …..
* Striped Jack was stale & fishy. Pork was dry. Beef was tough & chewy.
* Main courses pork & beef both shared the same sauce ??

Service
* Still water. Staff don’t inform customer when they open new bottles. Even though our glasses were 3/4 full, they just keep filling up to the brim. At the end, we were overcharged for 2 more bottles which we were sure we didn’t drink as we had sparkling tea, sake, wines & 2 shots of espressos.
* Wine by the glass. The moment the small amount is given to taste, it’s sold. Doesn’t matter the sample is oxidized & we rejected it. They take that as a pour & charged the glass without telling us.

Atmosphere
* Not a white tablecloth restaurant. Moody interiors. Artificial plants. Bad acoustics.
* Toilet very dark & musty.

reviews.text: Brought my partner here to breakfast with her on her birthday. Staff was super accommodating the food was insane. The flavours are really really out of this world and their interpretations of traditional and modern Malay food really makes you reconsider and rethink how you see food.  Fine dining prices though so if you are paying premium prices. I paid around $550 including service and GST, and I got the select menu for my partner and I. Will come again and maybe treat my parents.

Brought my mother to her first fine dining for her birthday. Mom enjoyed herself very much, loved the ambience, service by Hafiz, and found every single dish splendid. Surprised and impressed by how our Malay dishes could be elevated to such great levels of taste and presentation. Mom wanted to meet the head chef Hafizzul to thank him and get a photo with him but sadly he was away that day.

Regardless, grateful to have chosen Fiz :)

Great experience here. Brought my family over. It’s a unique opportunity to try south East Asian fine dining. Initially wondered how can south East Asian food be made into fine dining? But this really does it well - the food structure taste etc. is definitely at *good* fine dining level. Appreciate the communal dining at the end of the individual portions - Asian-touch not lost!

Really excellent food. There was nothing that we didn't like. Had gone with a friend for our joint birthday celebration. We'd ordered the 6-course menu. Everything was really delish, especially the duck. So much so, we had to ask for seconds coz the we felt the portion sizes were a little small. I understand chef would like to bring the sharing plates culture to fine dining, I think it would be better to have individually plated mains so the portion of meat, veges and rice is clear. Other than this... Everything was great. Service was attentive but with enough space for us to enjoy the meal and our conversation.

What a wonderful experience! The whole meal was a story about home and nostalgia. I highly recommend if you're looking to glimpse into the flavours and history of South East Asia. Also recommended that you go with good company as the menu is designed to be shared.

reviews.text: Absolutely every dish is superb! Former Master Chef Mr Woo Wai Leong and his crews were excellent in their services, explanations and presentation of food! What a memorable night for me and my wife’s wedding anniversary! Highly recommended!

A total of 12 courses included dessert.
Only one impressed me, but 4 for my friend.
But we both agreed the beef cheek is last, and the Murray cod Rillette is the best.

Restaurant Ibid provided an outstanding dining experience. The food surpassed our expectations, delivering a truly awesome culinary journey. From ambiance to flavor, every aspect contributed to a memorable evening. Highly recommended.

Exceptional experience from start to finish.

A warm and inviting ambiance from the crew set the stage right, followed by a brief introduction on every dish served and occasional interactions with Chef Woo.

Each dish was a symphony of flavors with a meticulous blend of creativity and expertise - a delightful balance between classic and innovative creations.

Loved it.

[Late review]

Visited in June 2023

Ibid had been on my list for a long time and what a great experience it was. Not many restaurants can command a 4.9/5 rating on Google after 700+ reviews and one can see why. The menu is well thought out and the dish preparations are absolutely perfect. The Wagyu, Cod and Risotto dishes were brilliant and the desserts were great too.

Service is really good. Chef Leong was also kind to have a long conversation on the fine dining scene in SG and provided some great insights on certain places to visit outside of SG.

A definite recommendation for all residents of SG. This restaurant must be on your places to try.

formatted_address: 3 Fullerton Rd, #02-01/02/03 The Fullerton Waterboat House, Singapore 049215
name: Restaurant Matera

reviews.text:
Cozy and located at a charismatic location.  The establishment provided customisable ala carte two to four courses lunch and an omakase six courses lunch. It sounded appealing but you needed to choose dessert or cheese as one of your ala carte courses. The cheeses plate was fine but the Japanese melon was disappointing. It also seems weird if I only ordered the Onion dish with dessert if I choose to have a two course lunch.

The foods were generally delicious but the ones that left a strong impression were the nicely warmed up Focaccia bread and the complimentary peppery spaghetti. The slightly spicy spaghetti was savoury and brought enough heat to the overall courses.

The waiting staffs were polite and friendly. They were slightly nervous maybe because we were their first and only lunch diners. It was unfortunate that tap water wasn’t available and we paid for sparkling water. It was a hot day and I wasn’t even offered ice to go with the water.

Really enjoyed our dinner here. Perfectly balanced between Asian and Italian. My favorite was the Beef Tendon Gnocchi. But more than that the anchovy dip that was part of the amuse-bouche was so good we had to ask for a second serving! My husband who isn’t big on desserts found the Green Melon Tofu Icecream extremely memorable. And while I enjoyed his dessert I was throughly happy with my Affogato.

We had a wonderful lunch in Matera, my best friend! It is our first time here, and we enjoyed the 4 course menu, every single dish is with seasonal ingredients, rich in flavor, We would like to highlight few talents here: Mr. Alvin, Mr. Arthur, Miss. Hailey, Miss. Mong. We were being taken care of,  they offered the best service. We will definitely come back with more friends, family.

A truly spectacular dining experience at Restaurant Matera. The meal completely took my breath away. A tour de force of flavour and finesse. Ordered the 8-course dinner menu ($328). They do, however, have cheaper options (6-course at $288; 5-course at $248; 4-course at 208; and 3-course at $168) which is a welcome change to the typical one-size-fits-all approach for dinner at other fine-dining establishments. Snacks: The ricotta with wonton skin was delightful and very light. The combination of traditional Italian flavours with Asian influences set the tone for the meal to come. Next, the mala Kalamata olives were rather unique and are served at a decent size given how these are only snacks. Beef tendon chips with anchovy sauce was very unorthodox (in a good way) and highly addictive. Loved that the anchovy sauce had a bit of spice. The duck sausage and salted egg yolk choux saw a slight dip in quality as we were off to a strong start. My partner and I were expecting that the duck sausage would be solid. Unfortunately it was not and was mixed in with the egg yolk. Also, and perhaps this is a personal bias, but I have never found choux pastry to be of sufficient elegance despite the popularity which they see among various michelin-starred chefs. Things quickly picked back up with the star of the snacks/amuse bouche: the tartlet of pomelo, abalone and scallop. An absolute flavour bomb which managed to be simultaneously light and rich in flavour. This was followed by the bread course which featured focaccia which had been baked with Chinese wine, giving the crust a slight sweetness distinguishing it from regular focaccia. Soft and fluffy, it was a welcome reprieve from the tendency for bread courses at establishments of the same ilk to be heavy. The first course continued the strong start to the meal. A highly innovative dish of scallops wrapped in burrata jelly topped with a generous dollop of caviar and sat in a bed of burrata sauce and chive oil. A master stroke which takes a mainstay of Italian cuisine and elevates it by utilising it in two highly unorthodox ways. The second course somehow managed to top the first, showcasing Chef Bjoern Alexander’s inventiveness. Foie gras is of course a bastion in the world of fine dining, but Chef Bjoern adds a playful twist, marinating the plump duck liver in sake and mirin before serving it with grapes, which are similarly soaked in sake and mirin, alongside a Chinese tea jelly. When eaten together, the liquor marinade, sweetness of the grapes and slight sourness from the tea jelly work wonders alongside the rich, butteriness of the foie. Once again, highly unorthodox but ingenious! Next up was the abalone with Japanese corn in chicken jus with zucchini purée and abalone liver purée. A very good course as all the flavours work well together. The addition of the two purées helped to mellow the sweetness of the corn. This was followed by the ravioli stuffed with carabinero prawn and topped with dried scallops served in prawn jus and XO sauce. A delightful course with flavour combinations that highlight the Asian influences that Chef Bjoern draws from. The dish tasted like an elevated Hokkien Mee and I mean this in the best way possible (as I love Hokkien mee!). Before proceeding to the mains, the final course was a bafun uni pasta with cherry tomatoes in a seafood broth with chilli oil. It was a good dish, but felt slightly out of place in a menu that had thus far put innovation, culinary pluralism and experimentation at the forefront. Compared with all the previous courses, it was a stark contrast and its simplicity was somewhat jarring. Perhaps this was intentional, but it came at the expense of coherence. The first of the two mains was the pigeon. Sourced from Brittany, this pigeon was served with a farce of leg, pomelo, artichoke purée and chips all in a sauce of pigeon jus and Szechuan pepper. Following the underwhelming pasta course, this was a strident return to form. In sum, a remarkable meal which I will not forget anytime soon.
